Abstract visualization of object identity versus internal mutable state in JavaScript and React.We turned on React Compiler on a production Next.js app and most things got faster. Then we noticed our data table headers weren’t updating anymore. Column visibility toggles stopped working. In one case a chart table was showing columns from the previous API response even after fresh data arrived.
The quick fix was easy to find: add "use no memo" to the broken component and move on. But that felt like putting a bandage over something we didn't understand. So we dug in. What we found affects every React app that uses TanStack Table with the compiler enabled.

A Quick Primer on What React Compiler Actually Does
React Compiler (shipped stable in React 19) automatically applies the equivalent of React.memo, useMemo, and useCallback throughout your component tree. You don't write them. The compiler inserts them based on static analysis of your code.
The way it decides what to memoize is straightforward: it tracks the identity (reference) of values. If a prop’s reference hasn’t changed between renders, the compiler assumes nothing relevant changed and skips re-rendering that subtree.
This works beautifully for plain data: strings, numbers, arrays, plain objects created fresh on each render. But it breaks down for a specific class of objects: mutable objects with stable references.

The Concept React Calls “Interior Mutability”
Interior mutability is when an object keeps hidden state that changes over time, while its reference stays the same. From the outside, React sees the same object. From the inside, everything is different.
// This is what React Compiler sees:
render 1 → table prop = 0x1a2b ✓
render 2 → table prop = 0x1a2b (same reference, skip re-render)// This is what actually happened inside that reference:
render 1 → table.getHeaderGroups() = [{ id: 'name' }, { id: 'count' }]
render 2 → table.getHeaderGroups() = [{ id: 'name' }, { id: 'count' }, { id: 'score' }]
This is precisely how TanStack Table works. useReactTable returns the same object instance on every render. When columns change, when visibility is toggled, when row order updates, TanStack mutates that object's internals in place. The reference never changes.
This isn’t a bug in TanStack Table. It’s an intentional design: recreating the table instance on every render would be expensive. But it means TanStack Table is fundamentally incompatible with React Compiler’s memoization model. React’s team has acknowledged this: useReactTable is on the official incompatible libraries list.

Why "use no memo" Is Not the Answer
Once you know about interior mutability, reaching for "use no memo" makes sense as a first response. It tells the compiler to skip memoizing that component entirely, which means it always re-renders and always reads fresh data from the table instance.
"use no memo";
export function TableHeader({ table }: { table: Table<RowData> }) {
const headerGroup = table.getHeaderGroups()[0];
// ...
}It works. But it’s a blunt instrument. You’re opting an entire component out of every compiler optimization, not just the one that’s broken. And more importantly, it treats the symptom, not the cause.
The real problem isn’t that this component gets memoized. The real problem is that a mutable object is being passed as a prop in the first place. If you add "use no memo" and move on, you'll add it again the next time someone extracts a new component that receives the table as a prop. And again. And again.

The Root of the Problem: Passing the Table Instance as a Prop
The specific failure mode we hit looked like this: a parent component owns useReactTable, builds columns dynamically from API data, and passes the table object down to a child component.
// Parent
const table = useReactTable({ data, columns, getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel() });
return (
<>
<TableHeader table={table} />
<TableBody table={table} />
</>
);// Child - the broken one
export function TableHeader({ table }: { table: Table<RowData> }) {
const headerGroup = table.getHeaderGroups()[0];
// renders columns from headerGroup...
}When new API data arrives with different columns, the parent re-renders. It calls useReactTable again with the new columns. TanStack Table updates the internal column state. But the table object reference stays the same.
React Compiler sees TableHeader receiving the same table reference → skips the re-render → header shows old columns.
The issue is most visible when columns are dynamic (derived from data). With static column definitions, the memoization still happens but produces the same output — so the bug exists but is invisible. Dynamic columns make the staleness obvious.

The Fix: Stop Passing the Table Instance, Pass Derived Data Instead
Instead of passing the mutable table object, derive what the child actually needs in the parent and pass it as plain data.
The parent re-renders whenever its real dependencies change. Each re-render calls table.getHeaderGroups() and gets a fresh array with a new reference. React Compiler sees the new reference and correctly re-renders the child.
// Before — mutable object, stable reference
<TableHeader table={table} />
// After - plain derived array, new reference when columns change
<TableHeader headerGroups={table.getHeaderGroups()} />// Child - now receives plain data
export function TableHeader({ headerGroups }: { headerGroups: HeaderGroup<RowData>[] }) {
const headerGroup = headerGroups[0];
// renders columns from headerGroup...
}No "use no memo". No special handling. Just a component that receives plain data and renders it. Exactly what React Compiler was designed to optimize.

A Second Pattern: Reading State from the Table Instance
The same issue appears in a more subtle form when a component both receives the table instance and reads state from it — like a column visibility panel.
export function ColumnVisibilityPanel<TData>({ table }: { table: Table<TData> }) {
const { columnVisibility, columnOrder } = table.getState(); const columns = useMemo(() => {
return table.getAllLeafColumns().filter(col => col.getCanHide());
}, [table, columnVisibility, columnOrder]);
// renders toggle switches for each column...
}
This looks correct, columnVisibility and columnOrder are in the useMemo deps. But if React Compiler memoizes the component based on the stable table reference, the component doesn't re-render at all. table.getState() never gets called. The switches in the panel don't reflect what the user just toggled.
The fix: if columnVisibility and columnOrder are already managed as real React state (Zustand, useState, etc.), pass them as explicit props.
// Before
<ColumnVisibilityPanel table={table} />// After — columnVisibility and columnOrder come from Zustand store state in the page
<ColumnVisibilityPanel
table={table}
columnVisibility={columnVisibility}
columnOrder={columnOrder}
/>
export function ColumnVisibilityPanel<TData>({
table,
columnVisibility,
columnOrder,
}: {
table: Table<TData>;
columnVisibility: VisibilityState;
columnOrder: string[];
}) {
const columns = useMemo(() => {
return table.getAllLeafColumns().filter(col => col.getCanHide());
}, [table, columnVisibility, columnOrder]);
// ...
}The table reference is still passed — the component still needs it to call mutation methods like column.toggleVisibility(). But the values the component reads for rendering now come from tracked props, not from the interior of the mutable object.
This is the key distinction: reading from a mutable object is dangerous; calling mutation methods on it is fine. Mutation methods fire events (Zustand store updates, setState callbacks) that trigger proper React re-renders up the tree. It’s the reads that fool the compiler.

The Broader Pattern
TanStack Table is the most common example of this problem, but interior mutability affects other libraries too.
React Hook Form has the same issue: useForm() returns a stable form object. Passing it to child components and reading form.formState inside them can cause stale renders. The fix is the same: extract the values you need (formState.errors, formState.isSubmitting) and pass them as explicit props.
Zustand store hooks passed as props are actually safe. When you pass a hook function like useStore={useSessionsStore} and the child calls it, Zustand uses useSyncExternalStore internally. That API has a React-level guarantee: it bypasses memoization and forces a re-render whenever the store changes. React Compiler cannot override useSyncExternalStore subscriptions.
The general rule: if a library returns a mutable object with a stable reference, do not pass that object as a prop to a child component that renders based on its internal state. Derive what you need at the point where useXxx is called, and pass plain values down.

What About TanStack Table v9?
TanStack Table v9 (currently in public beta) rewrites its internal state model using TanStack Store — a signals-style store with atom slices, derived state, and selector-based subscriptions. State changes become visible to React at the proper granularity. The table instance is no longer a mutable object with hidden interior state. React Compiler compatibility is one of the explicit design goals of v9.
Until v9 stabilizes and your codebase migrates, the patterns described above are the right approach. They’re not hacks. They’re just making the data flow explicit in the way React Compiler expects.

Summary
Child receives table prop, renders from table.getHeaderGroups()
Problem: stable ref → compiler skips re-render.
Fix: pass table.getHeaderGroups() as a plain array prop instead.
Child receives table prop, reads table.getState() for render
Problem: stable ref → component doesn't re-render, useMemo never runs.
Fix: pass state values as explicit props from the parent.
Component has "use no memo" to work around staleness
Problem: entire component opts out of all compiler optimizations.
Fix: apply the above fixes and remove the directive.
Zustand hook passed as a prop
Problem: none — this is safe.
Reason: useSyncExternalStore bypasses memoization and forces re-renders when store changes.
React Compiler didn’t introduce this bug. It exposed a fragile pattern that was always one optimization away from breaking.

